This is a (multiple allowed):

* [x] bug

* CakePHP Version: 3.5.0 (but also newer versions)
* Platform and Target: n/a

### What you did
We have written a PSR-16 compatible wrapper around the `CacheEngine`. For this to work, we dynamically set the `duration` of the engine to the value of the TTL and set it back to the normal `duration` again after writing the cache key.

The useful part of our code:
```php
class CacheEngineWrapper implements CacheInterface
{
    protected $engine;

    public function __construct(CacheEngine $cacheEngine)
    {
        $this->engine = $cacheEngine;
    }

    protected function setTtl($ttl = null)
    {
        $defaultDuration = $this->engine->getConfig('duration');
        if ($ttl !== null) {
            if ($ttl instanceof \DateInterval) {
                $ttlTime = new \DateTime();
                $ttlTime = $ttlTime->add($ttl);
                $this->engine->setConfig('duration', $ttlTime->getTimestamp() - time());
            } else {
                $this->engine->setConfig('duration', $ttl);
            }
        }
        return $defaultDuration;
    }

    public function get($key, $default = null)
    {
        $value = $this->engine->read($key);
        return $value === false ? $default : $value;
    }

    public function set($key, $value, $ttl = null)
    {
        $defaultDuration = $this->setTtl($ttl);
        $success         = $this->engine->write($key, $value);
        $this->setTtl($defaultDuration);
        return $success;
    }
```

### What happened
This works for all `CacheEngine` implementations except for the `FileEngine` in a specific case: if the TTL of an item we want to save is more than the default `duration`, the data *does* get saved in the cached but never gets retrieved, because of the second clause in this `if`: https://github.com/cakephp/cakephp/blob/master/src/Cache/Engine/FileEngine.php#L197

All other cache engines to not check the `duration` when reading an item; only `FileEngine` does. Maybe I am missing some (edge) case, but I think the second part of this `if` statement can be removed.

### What you expected to happen
I expected my cached item to be returned when I retrieve it.
